questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is a matrix?

options.A: A single row of numbers arranged by increasing value, used to represent polynomial equations and their roots.
options.B: A circular arrangement of numbers organized by magnitude and sign, used to represent nonlinear transformations and differential equations.
options.C: A rectangular array of numbers arranged in rows and columns, used to represent linear transformations and systems of equations.
options.D: A rectangular array of numbers arranged in rows and columns, used exclusively to store data with no algebraic operations defined.

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is a vector?

options.A: A mathematical object with both magnitude and direction, representable as an unordered set of numbers in a space.
options.B: A mathematical object with both magnitude and direction, representable only as a $2 \times 2$ matrix defining rotation.
options.C: A mathematical object with magnitude only and no direction, representable as a single number on the number line.
options.D: A mathematical object with both magnitude and direction, representable as an ordered list of numbers in a vector space.

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is a scalar?

options.A: An element of any set (such as a string or boolean) that can multiply a vector to produce another vector.
options.B: An element of the underlying field (such as a real number) that can multiply a vector to produce another vector.
options.C: A pair of real numbers that can be added to a vector to translate it to a new position in space.
options.D: An element of the underlying field (such as a real number) that can multiply a vector to produce a matrix.

questions.question_text: What is a linear equation?

options.A: An equation where each variable appears to the first power with no cross terms, graphing as a curved surface.
options.B: An equation where each variable appears to the first power with no cross terms, graphing as a straight line or hyperplane.
options.C: An equation where each variable appears to the second power with no cross terms, graphing as a parabola or paraboloid.
options.D: An equation where each variable appears to the first power with no cross terms, graphing as a circle or sphere.

questions.question_text: What is a system of linear equations?

options.A: A single linear equation involving two or more variables, solved by isolating each variable on one side.
options.B: A collection of two or more linear equations involving the same variables, solved simultaneously for common values.
options.C: A collection of two or more linear equations involving different variables, solved independently of one another.
options.D: A collection of two or more quadratic equations involving the same variables, solved simultaneously for common values.

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is matrix multiplication?

options.A: An operation producing a new matrix whose entries are dot products of columns of the first and rows of the second matrix.
options.B: An operation producing a new matrix whose entries are dot products of rows of the first and columns of the second matrix.
options.C: An operation producing a new matrix whose entries are element-wise products of matching positions from two matrices.
options.D: An operation producing a new matrix whose entries are sums of corresponding row and column elements from two matrices.

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is the transpose of a matrix?

options.A: A new matrix formed by negating every entry, so that entry $(i, j)$ becomes $-a_{ij}$, denoted $A^T$.
options.B: A new matrix formed by reversing the row order, so that the first row becomes the last row, denoted $A^T$.
options.C: A new matrix formed by swapping rows and columns, so entry $(i, j)$ becomes entry $(j, i)$, denoted $A^T$.
options.D: A new matrix formed by swapping rows and columns, so entry $(i, j)$ becomes entry $(j, i)$, denoted $A^{-1}$.

questions.question_text: For a nonnegative irreducible matrix $A$ with index of imprimitivity $h > 1$, what does the Perron-Frobenius theorem say about the eigenvalues of $A$ that have modulus equal to the spectral radius $r$?

options.A: Exactly $h$ eigenvalues have modulus $r$, all real and positive, uniformly distributed along the interval $[0, r]$.
options.B: Exactly $h$ eigenvalues have modulus $r$, equally spaced on the circle $|\lambda|=r$ as $r e^{2\pi i k/h}$ for $k=0,\ldots,h-1$.
options.C: Exactly $h-1$ eigenvalues besides $r$ share that modulus, located at the $h$-th roots of $\det(A)$ scaled to $r$.
options.D: Only the Perron root $r$ has modulus $r$, but with algebraic multiplicity $h$ and a single Jordan block of size $h$.

questions.question_text: In the Schur decomposition $A = QUQ^*$, what additional structural property does $U$ have when $A$ is a normal matrix, and what does this imply about the decomposition?

options.A: $U$ must be diagonal, so the Schur decomposition coincides with the spectral decomposition and the columns of $Q$ are eigenvectors.
options.B: $U$ must itself be unitary, so the decomposition factors $A$ as a product of two unitary matrices with no triangular part.
options.C: $U$ must be real-valued, so the Schur decomposition reduces to the real Schur form and $Q$ becomes an orthogonal matrix.
options.D: $U$ must be Hermitian, so the decomposition guarantees all eigenvalues of $A$ are real and $Q$ diagonalizes $A$.

questions.question_text: For $n \times n$ matrices $A$ and $B$, the identity $e^{A+B} = e^A e^B$ does not hold in general. What is the precise necessary and sufficient condition for this identity, and what related determinantal identity holds without restriction?

options.A: $e^{A+B} = e^A e^B$ holds if and only if $A$ and $B$ share the same eigenvectors. Without any restriction, $\det(e^A) = e^{\|A\|}$ always holds.
options.B: $e^{A+B} = e^A e^B$ holds if and only if $A + B$ is nilpotent. Without any restriction, $\det(e^A) = e^{\operatorname{tr}(A^2)/2}$ always holds.
options.C: $e^{A+B} = e^A e^B$ holds if and only if $A$ and $B$ commute ($AB = BA$). Without any restriction, $\det(e^A) = e^{\operatorname{tr}(A)}$ always holds.
options.D: $e^{A+B} = e^A e^B$ holds if and only if $A$ and $B$ are both diagonalizable. Without any restriction, $\det(e^A) = e^{\det(A)}$ always holds.

questions.question_text: For a nonsingular matrix $A$, the 2-norm condition number $\kappa_2(A)$ quantifies sensitivity of the solution $x$ in $Ax = b$ to perturbations. How is $\kappa_2(A)$ computed from the singular value decomposition, and what value indicates perfect conditioning?

options.A: $\kappa_2(A) = \sigma_{\max}^2/\sigma_{\min}^2$, the squared ratio of extreme singular values. Perfect conditioning gives $\kappa_2 = 1$, as for any positive definite matrix.
options.B: $\kappa_2(A) = \sigma_{\max} \cdot \sigma_{\min}$, the product of extreme singular values. Perfect conditioning gives $\kappa_2 = 0$, as for projection matrices.
options.C: $\kappa_2(A) = \sigma_{\max}/\sigma_{\min}$, the ratio of extreme singular values. Perfect conditioning gives $\kappa_2 = 1$, as for unitary matrices.
options.D: $\kappa_2(A) = \sigma_{\max} - \sigma_{\min}$, the difference of extreme singular values. Perfect conditioning gives $\kappa_2 = 0$, as for normal matrices.

questions.question_text: Sylvester's law of inertia states that congruence transformations $B = SAS^T$ preserve the inertia of a real symmetric matrix $A$. Precisely what triple is invariant, and how does this differ from what similarity transformations preserve?

options.A: Congruence preserves the triple $(\sigma_{\max}, \sigma_{\min}, \operatorname{rank} A)$ of extreme singular values and rank. Similarity preserves the singular values including multiplicities.
options.B: Congruence preserves the triple $(n_+, n_-, n_0)$ counting positive, negative, and zero eigenvalues along with the eigenvalues. Similarity preserves only the characteristic polynomial.
options.C: Congruence preserves the triple $(\det A, \operatorname{tr} A, \operatorname{rank} A)$ but not the individual eigenvalues. Similarity preserves only the trace and determinant of the matrix.
options.D: Congruence preserves the triple $(n_+, n_-, n_0)$ counting positive, negative, and zero eigenvalues, but not the eigenvalues themselves. Similarity preserves the actual eigenvalues including multiplicities.

questions.question_text: The Krylov subspace $\mathcal{K}_r(A, b) = \operatorname{span}\{b, Ab, A^2 b, \ldots, A^{r-1}b\}$ has a maximum dimension $r_0$ beyond which it stops growing. What determines $r_0$, and which iterative method exploits Krylov subspaces for nonsymmetric systems?

options.A: $r_0$ equals $\operatorname{rank}(A)$ for every nonzero $b$, independent of the minimal polynomial. Arnoldi iteration is the standard Krylov method for nonsymmetric systems.
options.B: $r_0$ is bounded by the number of distinct eigenvalues of $A$ (tight for some $b$). Conjugate gradient is the standard Krylov method for nonsymmetric systems.
options.C: $r_0$ is bounded by $n - \operatorname{nullity}(A)$, independent of $b$. Lanczos iteration is the standard Krylov method for nonsymmetric systems.
options.D: $r_0$ is bounded by the degree of the minimal polynomial of $A$ (tight for some $b$). GMRES is the standard Krylov method for nonsymmetric systems.

questions.question_text: In the singular value decomposition $M = U \Sigma V^*$, the matrix $\Sigma$ is diagonal with non-negative entries called singular values. How is the number of nonzero singular values related to the matrix $M$?

options.A: The number of nonzero singular values equals the nullity of $M$, indicating the dimension of its null space
options.B: The number of nonzero singular values equals the determinant of $M$, indicating its volume scaling factor
options.C: The number of nonzero singular values equals the rank of $M$, indicating the dimension of its column space
options.D: The number of nonzero singular values equals the trace of $M$, indicating the sum of its diagonal entries

questions.question_text: LU decomposition factors a matrix as $A = LU$ where $L$ is lower triangular and $U$ is upper triangular. In the standard formulation with $L$ unitriangular, what values appear on the diagonal of $L$?

options.A: All diagonal entries of $L$ are equal to one, making $L$ a unit lower triangular matrix
options.B: The diagonal entries of $L$ are the eigenvalues of $A$, arranged in decreasing order of magnitude
options.C: All diagonal entries of $L$ are equal to zero, since only the strictly lower part stores multipliers
options.D: The diagonal entries of $L$ are the pivots from Gaussian elimination, equal to the diagonal of $U$

questions.question_text: In the QR decomposition $A = QR$ of an invertible real square matrix, $Q$ is orthogonal and $R$ is upper triangular. Under what additional condition is this factorization unique?

options.A: The factorization is unique when the diagonal entries of $Q$ are all required to be positive
options.B: The factorization is unique when $Q$ is further required to have determinant equal to zero
options.C: The factorization is unique when $R$ is further required to be symmetric positive definite
options.D: The factorization is unique when the diagonal entries of $R$ are all required to be positive

questions.question_text: The Gram-Schmidt process constructs orthogonal vectors $\{u_1, \ldots, u_k\}$ from linearly independent vectors $\{v_1, \ldots, v_k\}$. Each step subtracts projections onto previously computed vectors. What happens if the input vectors are linearly dependent?

options.A: The process produces a vector with infinite norm because the subtracted projections amplify rather than cancel components
options.B: The process produces a zero vector at the step corresponding to the dependent vector, since its projections cancel it entirely
options.C: The process fails to terminate because the projection formula divides by zero at every subsequent step
options.D: The process produces a unit vector pointing in an arbitrary direction, chosen to maintain orthogonality with previous outputs

questions.question_text: The ordinary least squares solution minimizes $\|Ax - b\|^2$ for an overdetermined system. The solution satisfies a specific matrix equation derived by setting the gradient to zero. What is this equation?

options.A: The inverse equation $A^{-1} b = x$, obtained by directly inverting the coefficient matrix $A$
options.B: The normal equation $A^T A x = A^T b$, obtained by projecting $b$ onto the column space of $A$
options.C: The singular equation $A^T b = \Sigma x$, obtained by applying the singular value decomposition to $A$
options.D: The eigenvalue equation $A x = \lambda b$, obtained by decomposing $b$ into eigenvectors of $A$

questions.question_text: When changing from basis $B_{\text{old}}$ to basis $B_{\text{new}}$, a change-of-basis matrix $P$ converts coordinates. If a linear map has matrix $A$ in the old basis, what is its matrix representation in the new basis?

options.A: $A + P$, a translation that shifts the diagonal entries of $A$ by the entries of $P$
options.B: $P^T A P$, an orthogonal transformation that preserves the singular values but changes the eigenvalues
options.C: $P A P^{-1}$, a congruence transformation that preserves only the rank and nullity of $A$
options.D: $P^{-1} A P$, a similarity transformation that preserves eigenvalues, trace, and determinant of $A$

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is the identity matrix $I_n$?

options.A: A square matrix with ones on the main diagonal and zeros elsewhere, analogous to multiplying by the number $1$
options.B: A square matrix with zeros on the main diagonal and ones elsewhere, analogous to multiplying by the number $0$
options.C: A rectangular matrix with ones in every entry, used to preserve the dimensions of any matrix it multiplies
options.D: A square matrix with ones on the anti-diagonal and zeros elsewhere, analogous to reversing the order of entries

questions.question_text: What is the inverse of a matrix $A$, and what property defines it?

options.A: A matrix $A^{-1}$ such that $AA^{-1} = A^{-1}A = I$; it exists only when $A$ is square with nonzero determinant
options.B: A matrix $A^{-1}$ such that $AA^{-1} = A^{-1}A = A$; it exists only when $A$ is symmetric with positive entries
options.C: A matrix $A^{-1}$ such that $A + A^{-1} = I$; it exists for any matrix including non-square rectangular matrices
options.D: A matrix $A^{-1}$ such that $AA^{-1} = A^{-1}A = 0$; it exists only when $A$ is square with zero determinant

questions.question_text: What is the dot product of two vectors, and what type of quantity does it produce?

options.A: An operation on two equal-length vectors that returns a single scalar by summing the products of corresponding entries
options.B: An operation on two equal-length vectors that returns a matrix by computing the outer product of their entries
options.C: An operation on two vectors of any length that returns a single scalar by summing all entries from both vectors
options.D: An operation on two equal-length vectors that returns a new vector by multiplying the corresponding entries element-wise

questions.question_text: What is a vector space in linear algebra?

options.A: A set of elements called vectors that can only be scaled by integers, satisfying specific convergence conditions
options.B: A set of elements called vectors that can be added together and scaled by scalars, satisfying specific axioms
options.C: A set of elements called matrices that can be added together and scaled by scalars, without any required axioms
options.D: A set of elements called vectors that can be multiplied together and divided by scalars, satisfying specific axioms

questions.question_text: What is a linear transformation between two vector spaces?

options.A: A function that preserves vector addition but reverses scalar multiplication, mapping vectors between two spaces
options.B: A function that reverses vector addition and scalar multiplication, mapping vectors from one space to another
options.C: A function that preserves vector addition and scalar multiplication, mapping vectors from one space to another
options.D: A function that preserves vector magnitude and orientation, mapping vectors from one space to another

questions.question_text: What is Gaussian elimination, and what is its primary purpose in linear algebra?

options.A: An algorithm using elementary column operations on a matrix to find eigenvalues of linear systems by reducing to diagonal form
options.B: An algorithm using elementary row operations on a matrix to compute eigenvalues of systems by reducing to Jordan normal form
options.C: An algorithm using elementary row operations on a matrix to solve systems of linear equations by reducing to row echelon form
options.D: An algorithm using matrix multiplication operations on a matrix to solve systems of linear equations by reducing to symmetric form

questions.question_text: The eigenvalues of a square matrix $A$ are found by solving a specific polynomial equation. What is this equation called, and how is it derived?

options.A: The minimal polynomial $\operatorname{tr}(A - \lambda I) = 0$, derived by setting the trace of $A - \lambda I$ to zero so diagonals equal $\lambda$.
options.B: The characteristic polynomial $\det(A - \lambda I) = 0$, derived by requiring $A - \lambda I$ be singular so $A\mathbf{v} = \lambda\mathbf{v}$ has nonzero solutions.
options.C: The characteristic polynomial $\det(A - \lambda I) = 1$, derived by requiring $A - \lambda I$ have unit determinant so $A\mathbf{v} = \lambda\mathbf{v}$ preserves volume.
options.D: The characteristic polynomial $\det(A + \lambda I) = 0$, derived by requiring $A + \lambda I$ be invertible so $A\mathbf{v} = \lambda\mathbf{v}$ has unique solutions.

questions.question_text: If $\mathbf{v}$ is an eigenvector of matrix $A$ with eigenvalue $\lambda$, what happens when $A$ is applied to $3\mathbf{v}$?

options.A: $3\mathbf{v}$ is not an eigenvector of $A$ because the defining equation $A\mathbf{v} = \lambda\mathbf{v}$ holds only for the original vector $\mathbf{v}$, not its multiples.
options.B: $A(3\mathbf{v}) = (\lambda + 3)\mathbf{v}$, because applying $A$ to a scaled eigenvector adds the scalar to the eigenvalue.
options.C: $A(3\mathbf{v}) = 3\lambda^{2}\mathbf{v}$, because scaling an eigenvector squares the eigenvalue while preserving the scalar multiple.
options.D: $A(3\mathbf{v}) = 3\lambda\mathbf{v}$, because eigenvectors can be scaled by any nonzero scalar and remain eigenvectors with the same eigenvalue.

questions.question_text: If $A$ and $B$ are $n \times n$ matrices, what is $\det(AB)$ in terms of $\det(A)$ and $\det(B)$?

options.A: $\det(AB) = \det(A) \cdot \det(B) + \det(A + B)$. The determinant of a product includes a correction term from the sum of the matrices.
options.B: $\det(AB) = \det(A) \cdot \det(B)$. The determinant is multiplicative: the determinant of a product equals the product of the determinants.
options.C: $\det(AB) = \det(B) \cdot \det(A)^{-1}$. The determinant of a product equals the second factor's determinant divided by the first.
options.D: $\det(AB) = \det(A) + \det(B)$. The determinant is additive: the determinant of a product equals the sum of the determinants.

questions.question_text: The rank of an $m \times n$ matrix $A$ is defined as a dimension. What exactly does it measure, and what is its upper bound?

options.A: The rank is the dimension of the column space (equivalently, the maximal number of linearly independent columns). It is at most $m + n$.
options.B: The rank is the dimension of the null space (equivalently, the number of free variables). It is at most $\min(m, n)$.
options.C: The rank is the total number of nonzero entries in the row echelon form of $A$. It is at most $\min(m, n)$.
options.D: The rank is the dimension of the column space (equivalently, the maximal number of linearly independent columns). It is at most $\min(m, n)$.

questions.question_text: The null space of an $m \times n$ matrix $A$ is a subspace of $\mathbb{R}^n$. What vectors does it contain, and what does a trivial null space imply?

options.A: It contains all vectors $\mathbf{x}$ satisfying $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}$. A trivial null space (only the zero vector) means the columns of $A$ are linearly independent.
options.B: It contains all vectors $\mathbf{x}$ satisfying $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}$. A trivial null space (only the zero vector) means the columns of $A$ are linearly dependent.
options.C: It contains all vectors $\mathbf{b}$ in the range of $A$ where $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ is solvable. A trivial null space means $A$ is singular.
options.D: It contains all vectors $\mathbf{x}$ satisfying $A^T\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{0}$. A trivial null space (only the zero vector) means the rows of $A$ span $\mathbb{R}^n$.

questions.question_text: The column space of a matrix $A$ determines which systems $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ are solvable. What is the precise condition for solvability?

options.A: $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ is solvable if and only if $\mathbf{b}$ lies in the null space of $A$, i.e., $A$ maps $\mathbf{b}$ to the zero vector.
options.B: $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ is solvable if and only if $\mathbf{b}$ lies in the row space of $A$, i.e., $\mathbf{b}$ is a combination of $A$'s rows.
options.C: $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ is solvable if and only if $\mathbf{b}$ lies in the column space of $A$, i.e., $\mathbf{b}$ is a combination of $A$'s columns.
options.D: $A\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$ is solvable if and only if $\mathbf{b}$ is orthogonal to the column space, i.e., $\mathbf{b}$ projects to zero on each column.

questions.question_text: A basis for a vector space must satisfy exactly two properties. What are they, and what invariant do all bases of a given space share?

options.A: The vectors must be linearly independent and span the space. Every basis for a given space has the same number of elements, called the dimension.
options.B: The vectors must be linearly independent and have unit length. Every basis for a given space has the same number of elements, called the dimension.
options.C: The vectors must be linearly independent and span the space. Different bases for a given space can have different numbers of elements.
options.D: The vectors must be mutually orthogonal and span the space. Every basis for a given space has the same number of elements, called the dimension.

questions.question_text: In linear algebra, what is the span of a set of vectors?

options.A: The smallest subspace containing all the vectors, consisting of all possible linear combinations of those vectors.
options.B: The largest subspace orthogonal to all the vectors, consisting of all vectors perpendicular to the original set.
options.C: The dimension equal to the cardinality of the set, counting the number of vectors in the collection.
options.D: The set of unit vectors parallel to the originals, consisting of all normalized versions of those vectors.

questions.question_text: When is a set of vectors $\{v_1, \ldots, v_k\}$ linearly independent?

options.A: When the only solution to $c_1 v_1 + \cdots + c_k v_k = 0$ has at most one nonzero scalar coefficient.
options.B: When the only solution to $c_1 v_1 + \cdots + c_k v_k = 0$ is $c_1 = \cdots = c_k = 0$, the trivial solution.
options.C: When all vectors have equal magnitudes and the scalars satisfying the equation have equal absolute values.
options.D: When the only solution to $c_1 v_1 + \cdots + c_k v_k = 0$ has the sum $c_1 + \cdots + c_k = 0$.

questions.question_text: In an inner product space, when are two vectors orthogonal?

options.A: When their inner product equals the product of their norms: $\langle u, v \rangle = \|u\|\|v\|$.
options.B: When their inner product equals zero: $\langle u, v \rangle = 0$, meaning they are perpendicular in the geometry induced by the inner product.
options.C: When their inner product equals one: $\langle u, v \rangle = 1$, meaning they form a unit angle in the induced geometry.
options.D: When their inner product equals the negative of their norms: $\langle u, v \rangle = -\|u\|\|v\|$.

questions.question_text: The trace of a square matrix $A$ is invariant under similarity transformations. What does $\operatorname{tr}(P^{-1}AP)$ equal?

options.A: $\operatorname{tr}(A) + \operatorname{tr}(P)$, because traces add under matrix conjugation.
options.B: $\operatorname{tr}(A)$, because the trace is unchanged by similarity transformations using any invertible matrix $P$.
options.C: $\operatorname{tr}(A) \cdot \det(P)$, because similarity scales the trace by the determinant of $P$.
options.D: $\operatorname{tr}(A) / \operatorname{tr}(P)$, because the trace distributes inversely over similarity transformations.

questions.question_text: What does it mean for a matrix $A$ to be diagonalizable, and what is required?

options.A: $A = PDP^{-1}$ where $D$ is diagonal and $P$'s columns are the pivot columns of the row echelon form of $A$.
options.B: $A = PDP^{-1}$ where $D$ is diagonal and $P$'s columns are linearly independent eigenvectors of $A$.
options.C: $A = PDP^{-1}$ where $D$ is diagonal and $P$'s columns are the singular vectors from the SVD of $A$.
options.D: $A = PDP^{-1}$ where $D$ is diagonal and $P$'s columns are the cofactor vectors of the adjugate of $A$.

questions.question_text: Cramer's rule solves $Ax = b$ for a system with a nonsingular coefficient matrix. How is each component $x_i$ computed?

options.A: $x_i = \det(A_i)/\det(A)$, where $A_i$ is formed by replacing column $i$ of $A$ with $b$.
options.B: $x_i = \det(A_i)/\det(A)$, where $A_i$ is formed by replacing row $i$ of $A$ with $b$.
options.C: $x_i = \det(A)/\det(A_i)$, where $A_i$ is formed by replacing column $i$ of $A$ with $b$.
options.D: $x_i = \det(A_i) \cdot \det(A)$, where $A_i$ is formed by replacing column $i$ of $A$ with $b$.

questions.question_text: For a linear transformation $T: V \to W$ where $\dim(V) = 7$ and $\dim(\ker T) = 3$, what does the rank-nullity theorem tell us about $\dim(\operatorname{Im} T)$?

options.A: The image has dimension $3$, since $\operatorname{rank}(T) = \operatorname{nullity}(T)$ whenever the kernel is nontrivial.
options.B: The image has dimension $4$, since $\operatorname{rank}(T) = \dim(V) - \operatorname{nullity}(T) = 7 - 3$.
options.C: The image has dimension $10$, since $\operatorname{rank}(T) = \dim(V) + \operatorname{nullity}(T) = 7 + 3$.
options.D: The image has dimension $7$, since $\operatorname{rank}(T) = \dim(V)$ regardless of the kernel's dimension.

questions.question_text: Which property is NOT an axiom required for a map to define an inner product space?

options.A: Positive-definiteness: $\langle x, x \rangle > 0$ for all nonzero $x$, ensuring the induced norm is valid.
options.B: Conjugate symmetry: $\langle x, y \rangle = \overline{\langle y, x \rangle}$ for all vectors $x, y$ in $V$.
options.C: Linearity in the first argument: $\langle ax + by, z \rangle = a\langle x, z \rangle + b\langle y, z \rangle$.
options.D: Submultiplicativity: $\langle xy, z \rangle \leq \langle x, z \rangle \cdot \langle y, z \rangle$ for all vectors in $V$.

questions.question_text: If $W$ is a $2$-dimensional subspace of an inner product space $V$ with $\dim(V) = 5$, what is $\dim(W^\perp)$?

options.A: $\dim(W^\perp) = 3$, and $W^\perp \subset W$ rather than being a complementary subspace.
options.B: $\dim(W^\perp) = 2$, and $V$ decomposes as the direct sum $V = W \oplus W^\perp$.
options.C: $\dim(W^\perp) = 5$, because $W^\perp$ always equals the full space $V$ for any subspace $W$.
options.D: $\dim(W^\perp) = 3$, and $V$ decomposes as the direct sum $V = W \oplus W^\perp$.

questions.question_text: According to the spectral theorem, what special decomposition does every real symmetric matrix $A$ admit?

options.A: $A = LU$ where $L$ is lower triangular and $U$ is upper triangular, guaranteed for all symmetric matrices.
options.B: $A = Q\Lambda Q^T$ where $Q$ is any invertible matrix, $\Lambda$ is diagonal with complex eigenvalues in conjugate pairs.
options.C: $A = Q\Lambda Q^T$ where $Q$ is orthogonal, $\Lambda$ is diagonal with real eigenvalues, from an orthonormal eigenvector basis.
options.D: $A = U\Sigma V^T$ where $U, V$ are orthogonal and $\Sigma$ is diagonal with nonnegative singular values.

questions.question_text: Which condition is equivalent to a symmetric real matrix $M$ being positive definite?

options.A: The trace of $M$ is strictly positive, which alone guarantees $x^T M x > 0$ for all nonzero $x$.
options.B: All eigenvalues of $M$ are nonnegative, and $M$ can be factored as $M = B + B^T$ for some invertible $B$.
options.C: All diagonal entries of $M$ are strictly positive, which is necessary and sufficient for positive definiteness.
options.D: All eigenvalues of $M$ are strictly positive, and there exists an invertible $B$ such that $M = B^T B$.

questions.question_text: How do the Frobenius norm and spectral norm of a matrix differ in terms of singular values $\sigma_1 \geq \sigma_2 \geq \cdots$?

options.A: $\|A\|_F = \sigma_1$ uses only the largest singular value; $\|A\|_2 = \sqrt{\sigma_1^2 + \sigma_2^2 + \cdots}$ sums all squares.
options.B: $\|A\|_F = \sqrt{\sigma_1^2 + \sigma_2^2 + \cdots}$ uses all singular values; $\|A\|_2 = \sigma_n$ uses the smallest.
options.C: $\|A\|_F = \sigma_1 + \sigma_2 + \cdots$ sums all singular values; $\|A\|_2 = \sigma_1 \cdot \sigma_2 \cdots$ multiplies them.
options.D: $\|A\|_F = \sqrt{\sigma_1^2 + \sigma_2^2 + \cdots}$ uses all singular values; $\|A\|_2 = \sigma_1$ uses only the largest.

questions.question_text: In the Jordan normal form of a matrix, what determines the number of Jordan blocks associated with a given eigenvalue $\lambda_i$?

options.A: The algebraic multiplicity of $\lambda_i$, which equals the exponent of $(\lambda - \lambda_i)$ in the characteristic polynomial
options.B: The geometric multiplicity of $\lambda_i$, which equals $\dim \ker(A - \lambda_i I)$, the dimension of the eigenspace
options.C: The rank deficiency of $(A - \lambda_i I)^2$, which equals the total number of generalized eigenvectors for $\lambda_i$
options.D: The index of nilpotency of $(A - \lambda_i I)$, which equals the size of the largest Jordan block for $\lambda_i$

questions.question_text: If $V$ has dimension $m$ and $W$ has dimension $n$, what is $\dim(V \otimes W)$, and what forms a basis for the tensor product space?

options.A: The dimension is $m + n$, with basis $\{v_i \oplus w_j\}$ formed by direct sums of basis elements from $V$ and $W$
options.B: The dimension is $\min(m, n)$, with basis $\{v_i \otimes w_i\}$ formed by matched-index tensor products of basis elements
options.C: The dimension is $mn$, with basis $\{v_i \otimes w_j\}$ formed by all pairwise tensor products of basis elements from $V$ and $W$
options.D: The dimension is $\binom{m+n}{2}$, with basis formed by symmetric tensor products of basis elements from $V$ and $W$

questions.question_text: In the exterior algebra $\Lambda(V)$ of an $n$-dimensional vector space $V$, what is $\dim(\Lambda^k(V))$, and why does $\Lambda^k(V) = 0$ for $k > n$?

options.A: $\dim(\Lambda^k(V)) = k!\binom{n}{k}$ because each $k$-blade has $k!$ distinct ordered arrangements, and ordering is not quotiented out in the exterior algebra
options.B: $\dim(\Lambda^k(V)) = n^k$ because each factor in the wedge product independently ranges over all $n$ basis vectors
options.C: $\dim(\Lambda^k(V)) = \binom{n+k-1}{k}$ because the wedge product allows symmetric repetitions, so combinations with replacement of $k$ vectors from $n$ are counted
options.D: $\dim(\Lambda^k(V)) = \binom{n}{k}$ because the antisymmetry $v \wedge v = 0$ forces any wedge product of $k > n$ vectors to vanish

questions.question_text: Which of the four Moore-Penrose conditions ensures that the pseudoinverse $A^+$ is unique rather than merely a generalized inverse?

options.A: The commutativity condition $AA^+ = A^+A$ together with the reflexive condition $A^+AA^+ = A^+$ ensuring symmetry of the solution
options.B: The Hermiticity conditions $(AA^+)^* = AA^+$ and $(A^+A)^* = A^+A$, which force $AA^+$ and $A^+A$ to be orthogonal projections
options.C: The idempotency conditions $AA^+A = A$ and $A^+AA^+ = A^+$, which force $AA^+$ and $A^+A$ to be projection operators
options.D: The norm-minimality condition $\|A^+\| = \min$ together with the range condition $\text{ran}(A^+) = \text{ran}(A^*)$ ensuring optimality

questions.question_text: The Cayley-Hamilton theorem states $p_A(A) = 0$. How does this enable expressing $A^{-1}$ as a polynomial in $A$ for invertible $A$?

options.A: Substituting $A^{-1}$ for $\lambda$ in the characteristic polynomial $p_A(\lambda)$ directly gives $p_A(A^{-1}) = 0$, so $A^{-1}$ is a root of $p_A$
options.B: Factoring $p_A(A) = (A - \lambda_1 I)\cdots(A - \lambda_n I) = 0$ and inverting each factor yields a product formula for $A^{-1}$
options.C: Applying $p_A(A) = 0$ to each eigenvector in the eigenbasis and inverting each corresponding eigenvalue independently yields $A^{-1}$ in diagonalized polynomial form
options.D: Rearranging $A^n + c_{n-1}A^{n-1} + \cdots + c_0 I = 0$ and dividing by $A$ yields $A^{-1}$ as a degree $n{-}1$ polynomial in $A$

questions.question_text: In the Smith normal form $SAT = \text{diag}(\alpha_1, \ldots, \alpha_r, 0, \ldots)$ over a PID, how are the invariant factors $\alpha_i$ related to the minors of $A$?

options.A: $\alpha_i = \gcd(d_i(A), d_{i+1}(A))$, where $d_i(A)$ is the determinant of the leading $i \times i$ submatrix of $A$
options.B: $\alpha_i = d_i(A)/d_{i-1}(A)$, where $d_i(A)$ is the GCD of all $i \times i$ minors of $A$ and $d_0(A) = 1$
options.C: $\alpha_i = d_i(A) \cdot d_{i-1}(A)$, where $d_i(A)$ is the LCM of all $i \times i$ minors of $A$ and $d_0(A) = 1$
options.D: $\alpha_i = d_i(A) - d_{i-1}(A)$, where $d_i(A)$ is the sum of all $i \times i$ minors of $A$ and $d_0(A) = 0$
